  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the types of pain during pregnancy?",
  "response": "During pregnancy, women may experience various types of pain due to the physical and hormonal changes occurring in their bodies. Here are some common types of pain associated with pregnancy:\n\n1. **Round Ligament Pain**: This sharp or pulling pain typically occurs in the lower abdomen or pelvis and is caused by the stretching of the round ligaments that support the uterus as it grows.\n\n2. **Back Pain**: As the pregnancy progresses, the body undergoes changes in posture and weight distribution, often leading to lower back pain.\n\n3. **Pelvic Pain**: Many women experience pelvic pain, which can be due to pressure from the expanding uterus or changes in the pelvic joints.\n\n4. **Abdominal Pain**: Mild abdominal discomfort can occur due to stretched ligaments or gas and bloating.\n\n5. **Headaches**: Hormonal changes, stress, and changes in sleep patterns can contribute to tension headaches or migraines during pregnancy.\n\n6. **Sciatica**: Compression of the sciatic nerve can cause pain that radiates from the lower back down through the hips and legs.\n\n7. **Carpal Tunnel Syndrome**: Swelling and fluid retention during pregnancy can compress the median nerve in the wrist, leading to pain, tingling, or numbness in the hands and fingers.\n\n8. **Breast and Nipple Pain**: Hormonal changes can lead to breast tenderness and sensitivity as the body prepares for breastfeeding.\n\n9. **Leg Cramps**: Many women experience leg cramps, especially at night, often due to changes in circulation and pressure on blood vessels.\n\n10. **Labor Pain**: As the due date approaches, women may begin to experience contractions and associated pain as the body prepares for labor.\n\n11. **Postpartum Pain**: After delivery, women may experience pain related to recovery from childbirth, including perineal pain, uterine cramping, and breast discomfort if breastfeeding.\n\nIf pain is severe or persistent, it is essential for pregnant individuals to consult their healthcare provider to rule out any complications or obtain appropriate treatment.",
